## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests, 9 Critical findings, 0 High, 1 Medium, 0 Low**

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test class. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called (achieving high code coverage), but almost nothing meaningful is verified. These tests will pass even if the production code is completely broken — as long as it doesn't throw.

---

### 🔴 Critical — False Confidence

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic)

The entire class systematically calls every method on `ProductCatalog` in declaration order with no meaningful assertions. This inflates coverage to ~95% while verifying almost nothing.

---

#### 2. No Assertion — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)

```csharp
// BEFORE — proves nothing
_catalog.AddProduct(product);

// AFTER — verify the product is actually persisted
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
```

#### 3. Trivial `IsNotNull` — `GetProduct_Works` (line 23)

Only checks the result isn't null. Doesn't verify the *correct* product was returned.

```csharp
// BEFORE
Assert.IsNotNull(result);

// AFTER
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", result?.Sku);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", result?.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, result?.Price);
```

#### 4. No Assertion — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 33)

Never verifies the price was actually updated.

```csharp
// AFTER
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
```

#### 5. No Assertion — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39)

Never verifies the product was actually removed.

```csharp
// AFTER
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

#### 6. Trivial `IsNotNull` — `SearchProducts_Works` (line 46)

Doesn't verify the search returned the right product or excluded the wrong one.

```csharp
// AFTER
var results = _catalog.Search("Widget");
Assert.AreEqual(1, results.Count);
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", results[0].Sku);
```

#### 7. Trivial `IsNotNull` — `GetAllProducts_Works` (line 55)

Doesn't verify the count or contents.

```csharp
// AFTER
var all = _catalog.GetAll();
Assert.AreEqual(1, all.Count);
```

#### 8. No Assertion — `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)

The return value isn't even captured into a variable that's asserted.

```csharp
// AFTER
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();
Assert.AreEqual(1, count);
